#section-heading("I", "The Setup: Half of This Conversation Never Happened")

You had a fight last week. Or what almost-was-a-fight. Someone — possibly you — said _I just don't think you respect me_, and the other person said _I do respect you_, and somehow that was the worst answer they could have given. The thing got bigger. Or it got quieter, which is sometimes worse. You went to bed thinking the fight was about respect. You woke up suspecting it was about something else, but you could not quite say what.

Or it was not a fight. It was your mom on the phone, sighing in a particular way at the end of a sentence. It was your roommate not making eye contact when you walked into the kitchen. It was your partner answering your text seven hours later with a thumbs-up emoji. Half the conversation never actually happened, and you were already losing it.

Or it was the conversation in your own head at 3 AM. The one with the boss. Or the parent. Or the version of yourself from eight years ago who is still, somehow, on the witness stand. That one does not end. It just goes underground for a while.

A few small clearings before we go any further.

This is not a script. If you came looking for sentences to memorize and aim at your mother-in-law, you are about to be disappointed. People who try to deploy NVC like a smart bomb sound like hostages reading a statement, and the people they aim it at can tell. The hostage knows. The captor knows. Everybody in the kitchen knows.

It is also not a technique for being nicer. _Nice_ is mostly a performance — usually the one we put on right before we lose it. Nonviolent Communication is not interested in your manners. It is interested in whether anything true is moving between two people, including the two people who happen to live inside your own skull.

It is not therapy. Your therapist is your therapist. They have insurance and a couch and they are paid to hold a particular kind of attention for fifty minutes at a time. NVC is for the rest of your week. The dishes. The boss email. The text from your sister at 9:47 on a Tuesday that made your chest tighten before you had even read it.

And it is not, despite some of the marketing in some quarters, a more dignified way to win an argument. If you are still trying to win, you have already lost the only thing that mattered.

#asterism-break

So what is it.

It is a way of speaking — and a way of listening, and a way of talking to yourself — that, after enough practice, starts doing something to the room. Something most communication does not do. Language doesn't just describe reality; it writes it. A sentence like _you are selfish_ renders someone permanent and opens a courtroom. It uses the _is of identity_ — a grammatical habit that flattens a fluid human being into a fixed, inescapable category. A sentence like _I am hurt and I am longing for partnership_ does something else entirely to the person who says it and the person who hears it. That is working magic, in the oldest and most operative sense of the word — not the woo, but language that changes the state of the people in earshot, including the speaker. Some of the clearest versions appear in Rosenberg's own pages, where the man is a great deal more political and a great deal weirder than his reputation suggests.

At first, admittedly, it sounds stilted. _I'm feeling X and I'm needing Y and would you be willing to Z._ Yes. We know. The scaffolding is awkward. So is a beginner doing tai chi. So is a beginner doing anything that touches the nervous system at depth — at the start it looks like cosplay, and then one day it doesn't, and you can't quite say when it changed. People who use this well do not, eventually, sound like they are using it. They sound like themselves, only more clearly.

#divider

Most of what follows assumes that the things you have been calling _facts_ about your relationships, your conversations, and your own inner life are mostly stories. They are sometimes good stories. They are sometimes very, very old stories, told to you by someone who is no longer in the room. Just notice the suspicion in the air.

Nothing in here is trying to convert you. You can put it down. You can argue with it. You can do it badly. You _will_ do it badly. So will everyone you practice with. That is not a problem with the practice. That is part of how the practice works.

